Is there a way to add the ability to create a new text (.txt) file via the Context menu in Mac Finder just using the Mac OS? I’m constantly creating new txt files and find it cumbersome to open MacVim and save the file to a directory that may be many levels deep within my Documents. It would be so much easier to just right-click in Finder and see an option to create a new text file. I’ve tried apps like New File Menu 62 but they typically work once or twice after I install them and then they just stop working. Thanks.

Why don’t you explore the touch command.

tomalmy
Mar 2024

Use touch as KirkS suggests. But then do a Get Info on the file and check the Stationery pad box.

When click on the file (to open it) it will copy the file and open the assigned editor on it.

If you don’t like the location of the new file, click the down arrow in the title bar and change the name and/or the location. If you have a favorites folder defined for the location that will speed this process. But note that you can select “Other” for the location which pops up a Finder window, and then drag the destination folder ( from another finder window) to the pop up to select it.

I will state that the Templates in Microsoft Windows is nicer, though! But it’s been a decade since I’ve used Windows.

How long I struggled to create the best solution for this! Ultimately, I created a macOS Shortcut called “Create new file here”, which I launch via right-click → Quick Actions.

CleanShot 2024-08-27--21-53-241920×1423 81.9 KB

The Shortcut then prompts for a filename, which defaults to untitled.txt.

CleanShot 2024-08-27--21-58-571920×1394 55 KB

The file is created using a Bash script (touch command). If a file with that name already exists, it will append a number afterward.

CleanShot 2024-08-27--22-02-221920×1406 60.1 KB

Here is the Shortcut with the Bash script.

CleanShot 2024-08-27--22-07-121618×2066 97.9 KB

Make sure that the Shortcut is set-up properly to run in Finder and via the Services Menu.

CleanShot 2024-08-27--22-12-49730×1110 73.3 KB

I hope that helps someone out there! This took me forever to figure out. Now I use it all the time!

It is easily a feature that should simply be baked into macOS.

texjer
Mar 26

I think I might have found the best way to create text files in finder — but not through a context menu. I made this work using the Automator script below, and then making a keyboard shortcut in System Preferences. I’ve detailed the how-to here 6 on my blog.

Here’s the Automator script, use “Run Applescript” and “no-input” and “Finder.app” selected:

on run {input, parameters}
    tell application "Finder"
        if (count of windows) is not 0 then
            set currentFolder to (target of front window) as alias
        else
            set currentFolder to (desktop as alias)
        end if
    end tell
    set folderPath to POSIX path of currentFolder
    if folderPath does not end with "/" then
        set folderPath to folderPath & "/"
    end if
    set fileName to text returned of (display dialog "Enter file name:" default answer "untitled.txt")
    set filePath to folderPath & fileName
    do shell script "touch " & quoted form of filePath
    try
        if fileName starts with "." then
            do shell script "open -a TextEdit " & quoted form of filePath
        else
            do shell script "open " & quoted form of filePath
        end if
    on error errMsg
        display notification "Could not open file automatically: " & errMsg
    end try
    return input
end run
